  <chapter id="introduction">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <para>
    <application>GNOME App Install</application> allows you to add or remove programs with a click of a button. You can browse through the categories to find programs, or search through all of the programs using the search box. 
    </para> 
    <para>Only simple additions and removals can be performed with <application>GNOME App Install</application>. For more complicated needs, the <application>Synaptic Package Manager</application> is used.</para> 
  </chapter> 
  <chapter id="getting-started">
    <title>Getting Started</title>
    <sect1 id="installation">
    	<title>Installation</title>
    	<para>
    	<application>GNOME App Install</application> is installed as part of the
        Ubuntu standard installation, and should already be in your system.
        If you need to install <application>GNOME App Install</application>, you can use <application>Synaptic Package Manager</application>. Choose <menuchoice>
          <guimenu>System</guimenu>
          <guisubmenu>Administration</guisubmenu>
          <guimenuitem>Synaptic Package Manager</guimenuitem>
        </menuchoice> to start <application>Synaptic</application>. The package
        you need to install is <command>GNOME-app-install</command>.</para>
      <para>You may also install <application>GNOME App Install</application> from the command line using <command>apt-get</command>. To install <application>GNOME App Install</application> from the command line:</para>
<programlisting>
sudo apt-get GNOME-app-install
</programlisting>
      <para>
        <application>GNOME App Install</application> is dependent on the following
        packages:</para> 
        <itemizedlist>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>synaptic</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-gtk2</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-GNOME-extras</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-glade2</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-GNOME2</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-apt</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-xdg</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>GNOME-icon-theme</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>python-launchpad-integration</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        		<listitem>
        			<para><application>firefox|mozilla-browser</application></para>
        		</listitem>
        </itemizedlist>
    </sect1>
    <sect1 id="starting-GNOME-app-install">
    	<title>Starting GNOME App Install</title>
    	    <para>There are three ways to start <application>GNOME App Install</application>. Choose <menuchoice>
    	    <guimenu>Applications</guimenu>
          <guimenuitem>Add Applications</guimenuitem>
        </menuchoice> to start <application>GNOME App Install</application>. Enter your password when prompted.</para>
        <para>You can also do
        <menuchoice>
        		<guimenu>System</guimenu>
        		<guisubmenu>Administration</guisubmenu>
        		<guimenuitem>Add Applications</guimenuitem>
        </menuchoice> to start <application>GNOME App Install.</application>
        </para>
        <para><application>GNOME-App-Install</application> can also be started from the command line:</para>
<programlisting>
sudo GNOME-app-install
</programlisting>
    </sect1>
